      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, you want the **math** and the **business implications** without the **goblin-infested** nonsense? Fine, I will strip away the **goblin-infested** metaphors and give you the **actual retail math** you need to run a **clothing boutique**.\n\n### The Inventory Turnover Ratio Formula\n\nThe standard formula is:\n\n$$ \\text{Inventory Turnover Ratio} = \\frac{\\text{Cost of Goods Sold (COGS)}}{\\text{Average Inventory}} $$\n\n*   **Cost of Goods Sold (COGS):** This is the total cost of the inventory you sold during a specific period (usually a month or a quarter). It is **not** your revenue; it is the actual cost of the clothes you sold.\n*   **Average Inventory:** This is the average amount of stock you had on hand during that same period. You calculate this by taking the beginning inventory plus the ending inventory and dividing by two.\n\n**Example:**\nIf your COGS for the month was **$10,000** and your average inventory was **$5,000**, your ratio is:\n$$ \\frac{10,000}{5,0",
